Requirement

context pie Extract the context sequence of the mutation site from the genome and use a Lego plot to display the mutation pattern. Draw a pie chart as well.

https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1111/cas.14113 From https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1111/cas.14113

Figure 2 Mutational signatures extracted from the aggregated NSCLC dataset. A, Lego plot representation of mutation patterns in 113 NSCLC samples. Single-nucleotide substitutions are divided into 6 categories with 16 surrounding flanking bases. The pie chart in the upper left shows the proportion of 6 categories of mutation patterns.

Interpretation

4X4TCGAFigure 2 B Each color contains a 4x4 structure, corresponding to the four TCGA bases. Therefore, this chart is more suitable for displaying the relationships between the four bases than the commonly used bar chart (see Figure 2 B).

61X62X3 As for the six colors, you could also plot them in a 1x6 structure, but the authors 2x3 structure saves space.

3 The height of the bar represents the third feature (here, the count). Besides using the bar format, you could also try using dots, with the size of the dots representing the bar height. Alternatively, you could use a heat map, with the depth of the color representing the bar height.

Application Scenarios

3m X n4 X 4 Simultaneously displaying three features is particularly suitable when one of the features has an m x n structure, such as the 4 bases x 4 bases in the article.

lego

Drawing a Lego Chart

legobarplot3dRhttps://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/barplot3d/vignettes/barplot3d.html The Lego chart is based on the source code of the barplot3d package, with some modifications. The link to this R package is https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/barplot3d/vignettes/barplot3d.html

very_easy_input.csvmut_type6mut_context16 very_easy_input.csv contains two columns: the first column, mut_type, corresponds to the six colors in the chart, and the second column, mut_context, corresponds to the 16 bars in each color. The height of the bar represents the number of bars. Simply apply your own data.

data <- read.csv("very_easy_input.csv")

# lego
# Note: The color scheme and order of the reproduced chart differ from the original. The order of the pie chart and the Lego chart in the original is inconsistent, which makes it look a bit strange.
palettecolors <- c("#805D3F", "#72549A", "#5EAFB2", "#3F4F9D", "#F2EC3C", "#74B655") #6
mut_types <- c("C>T", "C>A", "C>G", "T>G", "T>C", "T>A")
contexts <- c("T_T", "C_T", "A_T", "G_T", "T_C", "C_C", "A_C", "G_C",
         "T_A", "C_A", "A_A", "G_A", "T_G", "C_G", "A_G", "G_G")
typeorder <- c()
for(type in mut_types){
    typeorder <- c(typeorder, paste(type, contexts, sep="."))
}

# 
# count
mut_data <- table(paste0(as.character(data$mut_type), ".", as.character(data$mut_context)))
mut_data <- mut_data[typeorder]

# 
# Run the following code to open a plot window. Drag the mouse to the desired angle and size, then save the plot.
legoplot.3d(mut_data, 
            scalez=0.015, 
            zlab="Mutations", 
            palettecolors=palettecolors)

3D Sometimes, we want to display multiple 3D plots in the same article at the same angle. To do this, save the angle and use it each time you draw.

#3D
# Save the manually adjusted 3D graph position and angle to a file
myMatrix <- par3d()
userMatrix <- myMatrix$userMatrix
windowRect <- myMatrix$windowRect
# 
# Save the angle to a file
save(userMatrix, windowRect, file = "par3d.RData")

Load the previously adjusted angle to draw the graph

(load("par3d.RData"))
## [1] "userMatrix" "windowRect"
par3d(userMatrix=userMatrix,
      windowRect=windowRect)
